{"id":"2007.09174","submitter":"Jonathan Monta\\~no","authors":"Justin Lyle, Jonathan Monta\\~no, and Sean K. Sather-Wagstaff","title":"Exterior powers and Tor-persistence","comments":"Title and presentation changed to acknowledge a known result in the\n  literature","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.AC math.RA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A commutative Noetherian ring $R$ is said to be Tor-persistent if, for any\nfinitely generated $R$-module $M$, the vanishing of\n$\\operatorname{Tor}_i^R(M,M)$ for $i\\gg 0$ implies $M$ has finite projective\ndimension. An open question of Avramov, et. al. asks whether any such $R$ is\nTor-persistent. In this work, we exploit properties of exterior powers of\nmodules and complexes to provide several partial answers to this question; in\nparticular, we show that every local ring $(R,\\mathfrak{m})$ with\n$\\mathfrak{m}^3=0$ is Tor-persistent. As a consequence of our methods, we\nprovide a new proof of the Tachikawa Conjecture for positively graded rings\nover a field of characteristic different from 2.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 17 Jul 2020 18:21:21 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 25 Aug 2020 00:02:39 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-08-26"}
